The architects saw - the office also includes a kindergarten
The Avriopoint office building in Brno is the new headquarters of the company Arch.Design.
But who would expect a mini kindergarten here, with everything that goes with it: colorful walls, creative furniture, a lot of toys and even a mini playground on the outdoor terrace.
This kindergarten has been available to the employees of Arch.Design since last year.
The architectural and design firm Arch.Design, from whose studios a number of well-known Brno buildings come, reckoned from the first designs for the new building Avriopoint with the premises for its company mini kindergarten.
In wise foresight, because most of his 90 employees (inside) are in the baby boom age and the company is concerned that the project assistants will return to their workplace as soon as possible.
Together with the possibility to work shorter, the kindergarten is another bonus that Arch.Design has to offer to its employees in the concept of their social program.
The civil engineers have it so easier to reconcile their demanding profession and child care.
The Mini Kindergarten is an original idea of the employees of Arch.Design and with the support of the management they managed to attract funding from the European Union and the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs for their project.
The company's mini kindergarten is financed by the Human Resources and Employment Policy Operational Programme from the European Social Fund and the Czech Republic's State Budget.
Thanks to this financing (compensation of CZK 2,8 million), the necessary facilities and equipment could be procured and qualified staff and operations are provided for a period of 2 years.
After the utilization of the funds (2 years), the company Arch.Design is obliged to continue to operate the mini kindergarten for another 3 years at its own expense.
The preparation of this project took a whole year, with the company Economy Rating providing active assistance in the application process.
The children are fully qualified staff - a nurse and a kindergarten teacher, the kindergarten can visit children without age restrictions, although most of them are over three years old.
And since this is about a mini kindergarten, only 5 children are allowed to be present at the same time, however, the day alternates over several children.
The kindergarten company is flexibly adapted to the needs of the parents, the children of all employees have the same rights in relation to the use of the kindergarten - regardless of the company hierarchy and their respective position.
Although it is a matter of individual education and care, the programme content in the mini kindergarten is nevertheless comparable to the framework programme for pre-school education.
The children not only play here, but above all they are offered excellent lessons - from basic knowledge to pre-school lessons, while they also learn English.
The classroom is not only equipped with toys and creative games, but also with a computer that is available to children.
What's more - the presence of young children in the company contributes to a friendly and positive corporate environment.
Parents can take a look at the children at any time and thus avoid the stress of late picking up the children from a far away kindergarten.
Parents therefore use their working hours more productively.
No wonder that natural and loyal employer-employee relationships also develop here.
In this way, Arch.Design is among the Czech companies that offer significant benefits when recruiting new employees, who are family-friendly and support their personal marketing through such programs.
A bone house still fascinates after 100 years. Check out the interiors of Gaudi
The roof looks like the back of a prehistoric lizard, the stairs like the spine of a dinosaur and the balconies are torn up fish owls.
This is the Casa Batlló of the Catalan architect Antonio Gaudi in Barcelona.
The local inhabitants nicknamed the house "Knochenhaus" with its organic forms.
Organic shapes, wild colors, the unusual use of stone, tiled splinters and mosaics, the facades reminiscent of scales and ubiquitous soft lines, all these are typical features of the Art Nouveau by Antonio Gaudi.
The facade of the house plays with dreamlike lines, tender colors and textures reminiscent of nature and living beings.
Only when you look more closely do you notice that everything is dominated by geometry, rhythm and thought-out order.
At night, the entire façade looks even more plastic, dramatic and the special illumination enhances the shine of the colours.
The same sweeping lines and intertwined forms also dominate the interior of the house.
Wave-shaped wood copies the window frames, railings, decorative elements of doors, even peepholes and mouldings.
The Batlló house in the Eixample district on the bustling shopping street Passeig de Grácia No. 43 was built by the reconstruction of a house dating from 1877, which was designed by architect Emilio Sala Cortese.
The reconstruction took two years and was completed in 1906.
The investor, the wealthy industrialist Josep Batlló, originally insisted on the demolition of the old and the construction of a completely new building, but in the end he agreed with Gaudí's idea of an unusual and cheaper reconstruction.
However, the Casa Batlló house was not designed by Antoni Gaudí alone.
He worked with architect Josep Maria Jujol.
On its drawing board the decorations for the representative apartment of the reality owner were created and also the use of mosaics on the facade was his idea.
However, numerous other painters and artists also worked on the design of the façade.
The joint work on the drafts for Casa Batlló was the beginning of a fruitful collaboration between Jujola and Gaudí.
Jujol also participated in the construction of Gaudí's Casa Milá house in Park Güell, which also houses works by Antoni Gaudí.
Shortly after its completion, the house was nicknamed "Knochenhaus" by the local inhabitants of its organic forms.
Others called it the special window opening mechanism because of the "gowning house".
It is also said that at the top of the building is the sword of Saint George, the patron saint of Catalonia.
But other sculptural elements also symbolize hidden religious motives.
Gaudí designed for the house a central heating system with ventilation channels and typical fireplaces that was unique at the time.
Her 45-degree inclination seems a bit bizarre.
In his work Gaudí consistently ignored all the building regulations of that time and was by no means misled by them.
Before the construction began, he obtained the corresponding building permit from the city but the information he provided about the planned reconstruction was so vague that the city fathers were so horrified at the completion two years later by the result that they demanded remedy.
The councillors also argued, among other things, that the construction with its pillars even intervened in the public sidewalk.
However, there were no changes, quite the contrary - only fifteen days after the district's request to do so, Josep Batlló applied for the approval of the rental of the two highest floors of the house - and it was promptly granted.
The homeowner himself moved into the lower floors.
In the gallery on the second floor there was a social lounge, on the third floor there were the bedrooms and private rooms of the apartment.
The ground floor was leased to a jewelry store.
The entire six-storey building runs through a staircase up to the roof terrace.
Due to the basic elements of the conversion, all right angles and straight lines were removed and replaced by curved and curved walls.
Gaudí also worked with a modern concept for the mutual connection of spaces.
The social part can be completely connected by the opening of the salon doors and thus a larger society could comfortably chat without having to renounce a certain intimacy during more confidential conversations.
In addition to a new façade, Gaudí's renovation also provided the house with a rather unusual roof and two further floors.
Gaudí's play with the light as well as the blue and white glazed tiles with which the courtyard is covered and the courtyards are also impressive.
The game of these two colors gives all floors of the house a maximum of light.
In doing so, he simply took advantage of the principle that white reflects the light better than dark colours, which on the contrary absorb sunlight.
Casa Batlló, which was included in the UNESCO World Heritage List in 2005, can visit anyone today.
On the first floor, the most spacious and magnificent apartment is open to the public.
The homeowners only decided in the year to take this step and this on the occasion of the 150th birthday of the famous creator.
When it was found that this was a rather profitable business, the visits were kept, even extended to other common and attic rooms, including the roof terrace.
The price to visit the monument is not a cardboard handle, however, it is 16.50 euros, students, pensioners, groups and holders of tourist cards receive 20 percent discount.
This amount exceeds the entrance fees to other Gaudí buildings in the city.
If you want to get to know the real atmosphere of the house with its dragon towers, try to make friends with one of the house dwellers and visit him at home.
The right mattress and the right bed top? Women have different wishes than men
Not the greatest bed frame, but the quality of the lying area - so mattress and rust make up the good bed.
However, these must complement each other harmoniously in order to meet the wishes of the concrete user.
Many things play a role in the selection - the weight, the size, the state of health and not least the sex of the sleeper.
The interior, in which mattress and rust are subordinated, is just as important.
Typical example?
In a weekend house where there is no regular heating, latex mattresses are not well suited, as they take much longer to "warm up".
In addition, they are significantly heavier than usual polyurethane mattresses.
And - they should be turned regularly.
Because if they don't have enough ventilating cans in the core and are still lying on a solid plate, moisture accumulates: So it is not excluded that under their mold forms.
Of course, the choice also plays a role in what you're used to.
Those who have been abroad for a long time, where very high mattresses with a soft layer are common, will be hard to get used to a low mattress with a hard surface.
"Well, all the hockey players who came back from the NHL have complained to me that they can't sleep properly here anymore."
"For their worn shoulders, heels and hips, they simply need a soft layer of visco foam (memory foam - a shape memory polymer)."
"Among other things, I recommend sugar-sick people who suffer from nervous system disorders, so that they can receive the "information" from the joints and the skin badly," explains Sylva Hadamcziková, who specializes in upholstered furniture.
That's why I bought these mattresses with Visco foam (Memory Foam) years ago for many ice hockey players, but also for other customers.
"Today this is no longer a problem, because such mattresses offer among others the manufacturer Tempur, the Italian company Magniflex or the Czech manufacturer Tropico."
And you don't necessarily have to be a famous ice hockey player to appreciate the advantages of the Visco foam.
This "miracle" actually works quite simply.
The foam optimizes its hardness and shape according to the absorbed heat, in other words, it nestles in the warm body.
Nowhere does it push, in the night you don't roll around like after a heavy fight.
You just sleep a lot better.
The viscoelastic foam also offers protection against decubitus (wound fire).
When choosing the mattress size, you should still add the length of the soles of the foot to the height, i.e. approx. 21 to 34 cm.
Man like woman, who is 180 cm tall, needs such a 210 to 220 cm long bed.
Each sleeper should have at least 90 cm of lying width, i.e. 180 cm together.
For single beds, for example for singles, 120 to 140 cm are attached.
For the sake of comfort and also for possible visitors.
Otherwise, the following rule of thumb applies to the ideal bed width: "If you are lying on your back, there should still be enough space for the slightly angled arms," says Ing. Helena Prokopová, the guild master of upholsterers and interior decorators, who has been dedicated to the problem of healthy sleep and the ergonomics of furniture for years and who also presents this topic at specialist schools.
With a double bed each needs its own rust and its own mattress, but be careful when shopping, so that the mattresses are also equally high.
Otherwise, nothing else is left but to mount the rusts at different heights and that is far from possible with every bed frame.
Foam mattresses should be at least 14 cm high, mattresses with feather skeleton 15 cm, of which at least three centimetres should be allocated to the mould layer and the fine cushion.
"With your hand or while sitting down, you can't feel the feathers," warns Helena Prokopová.
Each mattress requires a special type of rust.
Fully upholstered beds with mattress and underlay like co-grown Siamz twins have nothing to do in the bedroom.
These mattresses cannot be ventilated and the cover cannot be washed, which is already common today.
And since one loses between 0.2 to 0.75 l of sweat in a single night, it is clear that after five to seven years the mattress slowly becomes a huge (and clogged sieve).
This is also why experts reject advertising slogans, which promise a lifetime of up to 25 years, even lifetime guarantee, for mattresses.
Every thing has its ifs and buts.
And therefore a practical advice from the dealers: For mattresses of 120 or 140 cm width, do not shy away from the hygiene of washable, removable covers, yet it is recommended to use a mattress protector, which can be easily removed and washed.
Even if today mattress covers are usually made with all-round zipper, so that you get two halves after opening (immensely important for the washing process and the washing machine size!), the manipulation with larger mattresses, especially executed alone, often looks like the unequal battle between David and Goliath.
Do they have a solid plate in bed instead of a rust?
Get it out of here!
Or at most for a bed for unloved guests and for a single night.
Even so, they should use the plate with ventilation holes (unless there are any in it) and mattresses with feather skeleton and 15 cm minimum height with so-called pocket spring core and fine cushions.
Polyurethane mattresses do not belong on such a backing.
Latex or sandwich mattresses (also combinations of latex and coconut) are suitable for non-adjustable slatted grates with 14 to 18 slatted strips (lamels), always paying off with a larger number of slats, i.e. 28 or more slatted strips, with lumbar support in the lumbar vertebra area and the possibility to regulate the slat hardness.
On adjustable slatted gratings do not include mattresses with spring skeleton, as they do not react to the ergonomic adjustment.
In addition to the adjustment of the stiffness of the spring strips, special flexible shoulder modules are also offered.
This involves a special attachment of the spring strips, which enables the spring strips to be pressed in or even angled in such a way that they allow the point-by-point sinking of the shoulder of the sleeper.
Especially for men with broad shoulders an important thing.
There are even mattress manufacturers who have started using soft zones for the shoulder area in "men's mattresses".
The ladies are also thought of - they are given these soft zones in the hip area.
For the most demanding customers, point-elastic wing spring systems (lattoflex) or rusts with point-elastic contact pads with so-called multitorsion suspension are determined.
The pressure is distributed over several points, which reduces the voltage.
But - if you use a bad (too large and full) pillow for the right mattress and proper rust, most advantages are lost again.
Here, too, a rule of thumb: the pillow should support the head, its tips should reach only to the shoulders, so that the shoulder muscles can relax.
Therefore, a 50 x 60 cm pillow appears ideal, as the Scandinavians like it, for example.
In the lateral position, the pillow (together with the shoulder relief zone in the rust or the soft zone in the mattress) should balance the shoulder height.
Our modern mattresses have something in common with the former straw bags (filled with hay).
Modern manufacturers are increasingly using natural materials or at least their admixtures.
The new magic word "organic" is also used in mattresses.
Instead of petroleum raw materials, natural oils - such as castor and soya oil - are increasingly used to produce polyurethane foams.
Soya is probably used by all known manufacturers.
"Bio is the name of mattresses, which are made of materials of pure natural origin," explains Petr Vašíček from Tropico Plus.
Natural materials are also used in the production of mattress covers - one of the first was Aloe Vera.
But you can also treat yourself to microcapsules that spread fresh forest or lavender scents while sleeping.
Here, too, you make a difference between man and woman.
While a "cooling" plant extract from birch leaves is used in men so that the mattress cover can absorb the heat and cool the body, the covers for women have a "warming" effect.
Extracts from red peppers stimulate blood circulation, so the weaker sex becomes pleasantly warm when sleeping.
What about today's favorites?
Mattresses made of cold foam (it has larger pores with destroyed cell structure and is therefore more breathable than commercial polyurethane and much more flexible).
The combination of the various stiffnesses (hardness) of cold foams and visco foams creates multi-zone mattresses that know exactly where the head, hip and heel are located.
For a high-quality mattress, however, you have 7000 crowns and more to cover.
However, health mattresses are usually burdened with lower VAT, as they are considered medical aids.
Gumotex was the first Czech company to benefit from this advantage.
You see, saving on the mattress and rust is not so easy.
Every now and then there are special offers from manufacturers and dealers who offer two mattresses at the price of one.
For example, the Magniflex brand offers the Duofreeze mattress with visco foam with a quilted cover for CZK 11,990.
You get the second one for free.
It was the material Tempur that initiated the era of viscoelastic foams with open cell structure and high density at almost cosmic speed.
No wonder they were developed for NASA, because the astronauts are exposed to enormous overloads at the launch.
Tempur becomes soft with heat, in a cool environment it solidifies again.
So it adapts perfectly to the human body and distributes the body pressure in an optimal way.
It is therefore not only ideal for preventing pressure burns, but also generally increases sleep comfort.
Viscoelastic foams are not only used for mattresses, but also for other health products, such as special foot pads, which are intended to make the legs and vessels easier.
Local manufacturers, for example, use the foams Eucatherm C, Twinsaver or similar products.
More and more parents want human surveillance devices to control the kids
The fear of one's own children is growing and so more and more parents are considering monitoring them via GPS.
The system, which was originally invented for the search for cars, can locate people just as well, which would be helpful in such cases as the recent disappearance of nine-year-old Anička Janatková.
The device is currently about the size of a cigarette box but soon it should not be bigger than a wristwatch.
Many people have been terrified by the disappearance of Anička, so they look for ways and means to better protect their children.
Also for the price of an impairment of their privacy.
"We are trying to tell everyone that this is not about spying around, but about an effective means of reducing the likelihood of tragedy," says Petr Pilin of Macro Weil, one of the suppliers of GPS tracking devices on the Czech market.
"I admit that there may be abuses of such devices in individual cases, for example, if you put it in someone's pocket without knowing about it, but we haven't had such a case yet."
"Most customers really buy it for security reasons," Pilin adds.
In his opinion, however, the child should always know what purpose the "box" serves and how to use it in an emergency.
However, the child psychologist Dana Bočková points out that if a child doesn't like to wear such a thing, he simply gets rid of it.
"Even very small children show great creativity when it comes to deliberately losing certain things if they do not want to be controlled."
"The mobile phones at first aroused great expectations with the parents, but they can be switched off just as easily as these new surveillance devices," says Ms. Bočková.
In their opinion, it is also controversial whether such an institution actually helps in the event of an attack.
