The Ice University
At Gelato University near Bologna, ice confectioners are prepared for better seasons.
The three-day basic course for future Gelatieri has the largest influx and visitors from all over the world.
Where does all the ice come from?
From the Gelataio and the Gelataio.
The gelatian, in German somewhat ancient the ice cream confectioner, produces the cream according to all the rules of Italian figuremaking.
The Gelataio takes the ice cream out of the cold store with a spatula, puts it in the waffle and then sells it.
To know that, you don't have to go to Anzola dell'Emilia in the province of Bologna.
But if you want to know more about ice, don't pass the Gelato University of the Italian company Carpigiani.
The Ice University established the ice cream machine manufacturer in 2003 so that the ice cream from its machines can meet the high Italian ideals everywhere.
The three-day basic course for future Gelatieri has the largest influx and visitors from all over the world.
There are also several days special courses around the chocolate ice cream and internships in the in-house ice cream parlour.
Some people dream of a new career in the midlife crisis, others just venture on the smooth ice of their vague longings.
This time there are 40 participants from 19 countries from all continents - from Brazil to Hungary to Saudi Arabia.
Jacky, art teacher from California, loves the slow food movement and wants to offer a European quality product in the country of industrial ice cream in the future.
Anke from Berlin is a management consultant and wants to bag something her own after years in a annoying job.
Two young Egyptian women dream of opening an ice cream parlour in Cairo.
A man from Malta and one from Brazil wants to improve the quality of the ice cream in their bars - and the Canadian housewife Julia comes because her children love Italian ice cream.
Maestro gelatians Luciano Ferrari first explains to the participants the ideal properties of the perfect ice cream.
The decisive factor is not only good taste, but also silky suppleness and good consistency.
Luciano does not forget the icing of the national and even southern superstructure during his training: "Italian gelato is simply the best - and then there is still a lot of romance."
The first step to manufacturing seems to be quite simple.
Luciano dumps the basic ingredients milk, cream, milk powder, sugar and stabilizers into a large mixer, which heats everything to 85 degrees with an electronic program and then immediately cools down to four degrees.
Then he turns a tap on the machine, and out comes a pasteurized white base cream, basis for all types of milk ice cream.
The lecturer is immediately overwhelmed with questions: Can ice cream be produced only with natural substances without a stabilizer?
How can one let go of one's own desire to experiment?
Luciano warns against being misled by the zeitgeist.
Those who speak of ice cream "only from natural ingredients" may have used stabilizers - usually a natural product, such as guar gum from the guar bean.
Of course, you can make ice even without a stabilizer, but then it has to be sold within one day, otherwise it will settle in, and the customer bites on all the ice grains.
Certain variations on the basic mass are allowed.
It becomes more exciting with the aromas.
For the taste in the ice, Maestro Luciano distinguishes between the ingredients you buy in the fruit department or from the sweets of the supermarket.
There are also powders and pastes.
"The suppliers will all try to give you dozens of flavored additives."
"But you should just experiment."
Either with the fruit sorbets with sugar and fresh fruit.
Or just with the ice cream from the white base mass, which turns with eggs into yellow cream and with cocoa powder to the basis for all possible chocolate seductions.
Now the students are allowed to use the ice machines.
Luciano makes them four different types of vanilla, chocolate, mocha and hazelnut ice cream - with or without eggs in the basic mass, with more or less vanilla flavor or other natural additives.
The fruit ice cream varieties are also subjected to the same experiment.
More flavourings, more fruit puree - this is not necessarily better taste.
Hazelnut ice cream does not necessarily taste nutty if it contains more hazelnuts.
The most popular kiwi ice cream makes the working group, which uses more fruits, less water and slightly less stabilizer.
Luciano says that it is only a balanced mixture that really enhances the taste of a gelato.
Ice making is a math task: If peach puree is used with a lot of sugar, the sugar content in the basic recipe must be reduced.
An extra portion of sugar is required for lemon ice.
Luciano pulls out a device with which he determines the sugar content of the fruit varieties (Winzer thus measure the oechsle in the grape must).
Fortunately, tables make computing easier.
Making ice doesn't require as much physical use as it used to be.
Not only the device for the automatic manufacturing of the basic material helps.
There is also a device in which the finished ice mixture is simultaneously creamy beaten and cooled to minus temperatures.
Despite all automation, small breakdowns are not left out.
The Brazilian Gustavo gets himself and his classmates from top to bottom with fruit puree when the oversized bar mixer gets out of control.
"In every class," says Maestro Luciano, "it's just a matter of time before something like this happens."
Controllers in twilight
