Two facts are particularly striking in this year's September and October survey.
First, the good mood in Latin America
Secondly, the growing interest in democracy and its main institutions.
In many countries on the South American Pacific coast, the democratic movement has increased sharply (see Table 1).
In Peru, for example, where the economy has grown by about 6% annually since 2002, the number of supporters of democracy has increased from 40% in 2005 to 61% this year.
This trend can also be seen in Mexico, where the economy has been recovering since the sharp slump last year.
But only half of the respondents in Mexico and Brazil, the most populous countries in the region, are convinced democrats, which lowers the regional average (see Chart 2).
About 44% of respondents said they were satisfied with their country's democratic practice, which is as much as last year, but 25% more than in 2001 (Figure 3).
About 34% trust the Congress of their country and 45% of their government. Both values correspond to those of last year, but show a significant increase compared to 2003 (17% and 24%).
A decade ago, Latin America's economic crises undermined its efforts to achieve more democracy.
The fact that this continued during the global economic crisis may be due to the fact that the countries of Latin America have only experienced a short period of recession and have recovered rapidly.
In addition, the poor were caught by a stronger social network.
(According to reports from the UN Economic Commission for Latin America this week, the poverty rate in Latin America rose only slightly in 2009 and fell by 32% this year.)
However, there are strong differences in mood from country to country (see diagram 4).
