An Electoral Slack
No one had expected that the elections in Haiti on 28 November would be perfect.
But the facts far exceeded the fears of the electoral workers who rushed to help the battered country.
Overcrowded ballot boxes, multiple votes, ballots in the Rinnstein, destroyed polling stations and intimidation were only a part of the problems.
Electoral stations opened with hours of delay.
Many Haitians, many of whom had become homeless from the January earthquake, roamed around looking for a choice.
Some finally gave up.
A dozen presidential candidates, including some suspected leaders, demanded that the election results be lifted due to alleged fraud.
Some violent protests took place throughout the country.
Nevertheless, Edmond Mulet, the head of the UN mission in Haiti, described the election as "very good in many respects".
According to a cautious statement by observers from the Organization of American States and the Caribbean Community, "these irregularities, however serious they may be, do not necessarily invalidate the process."
In other words, the show goes on.
The electoral authority, allegedly committed to the unpopular outgoing President René Préval and his candidate, Jude Célestin, will announce the preliminary results on 7 December.
The expected final election is scheduled for January.
There is still hope in the election.
The two leading opposition candidates, rap musician Michel Martelly and former first lady Mirlande Manigat, have withdrawn their initial appeal for invalidity.
If Jude Célestin, who has little or no support for the voters, declares the electoral authority to be the winner of the final election, this could lead to problems.
Due to the cholera epidemic and the fact that more than 1 million of the earthquake victims are still living in tents, a low turnout was feared.
On election day, many Haitians were prevented from voting by a lack of organisation.
Shortly before the election, about 250,000 ID cards needed for the election were not yet distributed.
There's a lot at stake.
Donor countries consider a legitimate, recognised government as an important step in Haiti's reconstruction.
The Haitians themselves are of the same opinion.
Secretly in the middle
In the weeks following your husband's sudden death, Argentina's president, Cristina Fernández, experienced a wave of sympathy that pushed her popularity rate up by 20 points to over 50%, the highest since her election in 2007.
Whether you will be able to re-election next year depends on whether the grieving Cristina Fernández is more willing to compromise than her deceased husband, her predecessor and political partner, Néstor Kirchner.
The signs are not clear.
Néstor Kirchner, who guided economic policy even after his wife's election, often drew up budgets that did not fully take into account tax revenues, economic growth and inflation.
This allowed the president couple to spend the extra income at their own discretion.
On paper, the Fernández government lost the majority in Congress last year.
But the opposition is divided and Kirchner's death after a heart attack on October 27 led to further discord.
Some regime critics from the ranks of the ruling peronists stood behind Cristina Fernández.
But after chaotic meetings (where one parliamentarian slapped another in the face and others accused the government of bribery), Congress failed to approve the 2011 budget.
"I will not discuss this," said the President.
The 2010 budget is now also valid for next year, which gives the President even more opportunity to spend money at his own discretion.
The economy is hot: it is likely to grow by up to 9% this year.
The official inflation rate is currently 11.1%, but many private estimates - and wage demands of the trade unions - drive the value to almost 30%.
Kirchner, who took office in 2003, when Argentina was shaken by economic crises, declared growth and poverty reduction its main objectives, not the reduction of inflation.
He refused to cooperate with the IMF, harassed the private sector and cleaned up the National Institute of Statistics and Census INDEC, which subsequently improved official inflation statistics.
Can Fernández now take a more moderate path?
It has called on the private sector and trade union leaders to hold talks.
And according to official statements, wage increases are to be limited to 18% next year.
The high world market prices for Argentina's agricultural products have given the economy a strong boost.
But inflation undermined the growth spurt of a major devaluation in 2002.
For this reason, Cristina Fernández may want to rejoin Argentina financially to the rest of the world.
At the beginning of this year, the government entered into an agreement with securities holders who had rejected the country's previous debt restructuring in 2001.
Now, Fernández seems to be pushing for an agreement with the donors from the Paris Club, to whom she owes about $6.7 billion.
The Kirchners had always rejected a review by the IMF, as is usual elsewhere.
But last month, the Minister for Economic Affairs, Amado Boudou, announced that the Fund will provide "technical support" in the preparation of a new national consumer price index, which looks like this is the first step towards cleaning up the INDEC.
It is not known whether Fernández will be politically active after her term of office has ended, even without her husband's support.
If so, it needs the support of the middle class, which has largely enough of Kirchnerism.
When the Argentinians return from their summer vacation in March, the wave of sympathies that were brought to them will be flattened.
If she wants to win another election, she has to decide whether to keep many of her husband's political decisions quiet and quiet.
