Police Operations in China Will Be Softer
Like a training officer, Tang Shenbin walked across an urban square, checked his nervous subordinates and gave orders with military authority and muted voice.
He wanted his female members of the Chengguan - China's robust guardians of the urban order, feared and despised for their arbitrary raids and their tendency to violence - to impress the audience.
"Just stand!"
"Look straight ahead!"
"Show them," he whispered to them, "how pretty girls are!"
Four girls, barely out of the teenage age, with white gloves and identical olive green jackets and trousers stood tight.
Four pairs of black pumps were in straight line.
Four neat hats sat perfectly on the hair held with blue-white striped bows.
"For me, they look average," Mr. Tang remarked with contempt.
"Models are pretty."
Several governments have already tried to polish up the image of China's city inspectors.
In one city, all new applicants must have a university degree.
Guangdong Province introduced a bright blue uniform instead of the grey-green one.
Wuhan in Central China replaced violence with low-stammering: In 2009, 50 officials reportedly circled a misplaced snack truck and stared at the operator until he packed in after half an hour and left the square.
Xindu, a district in Chengdu with 680,000 inhabitants, wants to fundamentally change the image.
Since 2003, 13 women have been strengthening urban police patrols. They have been selected specifically for their looks, their good figure and their youth.
They're supposed to give the rough-handed police a softer, feminine aspect.
But unfortunately Scarlett Johansson would hardly be able to improve the bad image that the Chinese from these city commandos have.
That's right, according to the critics.
Unlike the police, these officials are only allowed to enforce urban laws by means of fines or other administrative penalties.
But the Chinese media routinely show a different picture.
In January 2008, officers in Hubei Province beat a spectator to death while filming a protest action against a garbage dump with his cell phone.
Last year, a training manual of Beijing officials was stolen and published on the Internet, describing how criminals can be beaten without bloodshed.
This year, a Shanghai watermelon trader suffered brain injuries after a handcuff with five officials.
A violent video game that can be downloaded from the Internet shows officials trained in China in an attack on street traffickers.
"Chengguan scares the government," the China Daily national newspaper lamented last year, after further controversy about tactics.
