Zapatero and the red line of Germany
Berlin has chosen to retain the euro, but at the same time has established conditions for the whole of the European Union.
The tensions in the markets have triggered a double response from the government.
On the one hand, José Luis Rodríguez Zapatero has presented new adaptation measures, from tax reductions for small and micro-enterprises, regulation of temporary work companies or the abolition of the 426 euro support for unemployed people who do not receive unemployment benefits to the privatisation of 49 per cent of AENA, the administration of Barajas and El Prat airports and 30 per cent of the state lottery.
On the other hand, the deputy head of government, Elena Salgado, with the help of former Prime Minister Felipe González, supports the criticism of Chancellor Angela Merkel as the person responsible for the current crisis.
How are these processes to be understood?
It is anticipated that Merkel's position is not a mistake in her public relations work.
On the contrary, it is a new round in the difficult process of redefinition of the euro.
Germany is taking a fundamentally new perspective on shaping our future, which conflicts with the maintenance of the traditional traditions of most of its partners.
In view of the resistance in Europe, Germany is beginning to speculate about three possible ways out of the crisis.
The first: A strong euro with Germany, Austria, the Netherlands and other countries, while the south would have to leave the euro area.
The second: the reintroduction of the German Mark - although this sounds more like science fiction at the moment - supported by a large part of public opinion, about 50 percent of the population.
The third: a transformation of the euro in accordance with German proposals. This means: more macro-economic control; strict budgetary management; punishment of countries that exceed the targets; possibly the cessation of payments of some countries and the extension of the costs of potential adjustment measures to the private sector.
The German position is clear and has been emerging for some time, so there are no excuses now.
First in 2009, when both the IMF and the European Commission provided incentives for deficits, and the German government pulled a constitutional reform out of its sleeve to prevent this from happening from 2016.
This was the first sign of the drift between what Germany considered necessary (strict tax plans and stable public finances) and the practices of its European partners, including France.
The second sign was set by the Central European country when Merkel painfully pushed out the decision to save Greece.
But the fact is that the political consensus in Germany, the public opinion and the published opinion were absolutely against the rescue of Greece.
Finally, in the last days of October, Merkel comes out once again with a clear position. It calls for a reform of the European Union's agreements in order to enable the rescue of a country while at the same time obliging private lenders to bear part of the costs.
This position was conceived as anti-European, as it advanced the Irish crisis and all the following.
But their proposal, albeit somewhat sweet, has been adopted, and over the next few months we will be participating in the reform of the European Union, which will enable these measures to take place from 2013.
Germany has drawn a red line that it does not intend to cross.
It says to everyone that - even if unpopular measures now have to be taken - the old functioning of the euro will no longer exist from this date.
2013 will be the birth year of a new currency area in which the opposing countries will be severely punished, forced to declare insolvent and, in this case, the private sector will have to cover some of the costs.
Germany shows us that we must take a hard course of growth, with high savings and investment rates, moderate consumption, improved productivity and competitiveness, and positive external balances.
The other alternative, which is based on debt and construction with huge holes in the balance of payments, as Spain has pointed out in booming times, will simply not be accepted.
The offer is clear.
And we would do badly not to understand it.
It's not just about driving the government deficit down to three percent by 2013.
The demands are much harder.
And the worst thing we could do under these conditions is betray ourselves.
I hope that the current turbulence will be more calm.
And that we will take advantage of the opportunities offered to us by spring 2013.
It seems that Zapatero has understood this as well, and his double announcement (the promised reforms after the discussion with the large companies last Saturday and the announcement of new measures from yesterday) points out that despite the criticism of Merkel, the hypothesis of creating order in her own house has prepared her way.
But the red line drawn by Germany is there, and it doesn't look like something would change.
Among the possibilities considered, the fact that we would have to leave the euro area full of less serious countries is not to be ruled out.
In this case, Germany could still tell us that it warned us.
Sport and regulation
Tricks like those of Alonso and Ramos in the game against the Ajax show inventiveness, but not the will to avoid a sanction.
The alleged exclusion of two players from Real Madrid (Xabi Alonso and Sergio Ramos) in the game of November 23 against the Ajax in the Champions League led to a lot of ink being shed about whether it was an unportable act or not and whether both players should be sanctioned by UEFA.
As is well known, the two players lost a few minutes before the end of the game (their team had already clearly won) and played several fouls so that the referee showed them the second yellow card.
In this way, and as Real Madrid would lead its group, the two players will meet the prescribed penalty for the next league match against the Auxerre and thus enter the next game phase without any cards.
Finally, UEFA's disciplinary committee punished the club's coach, José Mourinho, with two games and the players involved with different amounts of money.
The provocation of a yellow card under such or similar circumstances is not a new practice, it is rather common in the world of football.
It is so widespread that it is part of the ethos - the unwritten rules followed in this sport.
Part of the debate surrounding the case is that a team of the football club Real Madrid (who, in his anthem, pretended nobleness and honor and on other occasions punished his players for similar incidents) played the leading role, and on the dramatization by Mourinho, who added one episode more to his long story than theatrical and provocative technician.
In any case, the debate revolves around whether this behaviour, which is not expressly prohibited by the statutes, contradicts the principles of sport, i.e. whether these actions constitute a rule change. In fact, this approach adheres to the statutes of sport, but seems to circumvent its meaning.
In this matter, the damage to the sport spirit should be investigated.
The sports spirit defends the physical integrity of the opponents, an aspect that was not endangered by these actions, because it was not an aggressive game.
Another aspect of a clean game is to avoid that the opposing players take unjustified advantage of the counter team. Nor did that happen.
The paradox of the action of the players of Real Madrid is that it does not correspond to what we normally mean by false play or rule circumvention, because the circumvention of the rule was not carried out secretly to avoid a sanction, but it should be as conspicuous as possible in order to be punished by the referee.
The players waited and gladly accepted the sanction.
Another question is what kind of advantage the offenders drew from the deliberate fouls.
It should be stressed here that the rival was neither placed in a more unfavourable position nor benefited from the game played, because the obvious result of this action was that his own team had to continue playing with fewer players.
It is also not a useful strategy for the next game, because the club does not have these players.
The advantage is obviously that players start the next phase of the Champions League without cards that could threaten their participation in a future game.
But it is a long-term, to a certain degree uncertain advantage, as the team could eventually also retire. In addition, the players get a sanction with this approach and pass into the second cycle of cards, in which they do less than in the first cycle due to card accumulation.
This does not make it so clear whether it is really an advantage.
Ultimately, such practices are not directed against the spirit of sport, which includes strategic decisions in order to derive the greatest possible benefit from the rules.
In this case, the players did not want to avoid a sanction (this would actually be a clear case of rule circumvention), they rather wanted to choose when to submit to it.
They made a strategic decision to evade or flee without a penalty.
Although the boundary between inventiveness and the regulatory environment is blurred, I believe that this is a clear case of inventiveness.
I have the impression that polemics arose as a result of two factors: because it was about two self-exclusions and because of the nature of the provoked transmission of rules.
The damage done to the principles of sport by these actions is less ethical than aesthetic.
