Global plan for the renewal of lighting
Yesterday, in Cancun, the UN proposed a plan to renew the lighting of households, trade and industry in 100 countries with a view to achieving a reduction in greenhouse gas emissions (CFCs), which corresponds to almost a third of the additional reduction that needs to be implemented in order to stabilise the Earth's climate by 2020.
This ambitious plan takes its position in the steps of the concrete large-scale projects that the UN hopes to implement in Cancun in order to compensate for the absence of mandatory reduction obligations of industrialised countries.
According to the plan put forward yesterday, the main problem would be avoided in the form of the 1.8 billion tonnes (Gt) of CFCs released to earth due to lighting if the white-hot bulbs, which are still a monopoly of 50 to 70% on the market, were replaced by fluorescent or better still by LEDs.
Lighting is responsible for 8% of global emissions.
This corresponds to an equivalent of 70% of the exhaust gases of the global fleet.
In Copenhagen last year, large emitters such as the United States, China, Europe and others, including Canada, committed themselves to voluntary reduction plans to reduce global CFC emissions from 53 Gt to 49 Gt.
From this balance, however, it would be necessary to deduct 5 Gt in order to stabilise the climate increase by 2 degrees Celsius from today to 2020, in order to prevent it from getting out of control.
In the white glowing pears, 95% of the energy escapes in the form of heat, and the remaining 5% produce the light.
With the compact fluorescent bulbs, energy consumption is reduced by 75%, with the new LED bulbs, this energy requirement is reduced again by two times.
The compact fluorescent bulbs last between 6000 and 10,000 hours on average.
The new LED bulbs, such as those that the manufacturer Philips has launched this week - this company, by the way, has participated in the UN study - have a life expectancy of 25,000 hours and consume 80% less energy than a white-hot bulb, which suggests the savings of the replacement plan to be applied in 100 countries.
In addition to the fact that ese completely new light bulbs emit very little heat, they can also work with a control resistance.
And they contain no mercury.
Several specialists have shown that compact fluorescent bulbs have reserves, because they contain mercury and that they therefore have to be disposed of as hazardous waste, which is not always possible in developing countries, unless producers provide an acceptance point.
According to the report, however, the main source of mercury emissions on the planet is not the compact fluorescent bulb, but rather the coal-fired power plants, which emit much more mercury to generate the electricity wasted by the white-burning pears.
In the United States alone, these coal-fired power stations emit 25,000 tons of mercury per year.
The report sets out in detail the profits each country would make thanks to this international programme.
Indonesia, for example, would save one billion dollars a year in the purchase of electricity and eight million tons of CO2, which means an equivalent of 3.5 coal-fired power plants, whose construction would cost Indonesia 2.5 billion.
