Racist hackers and embittered spies
The affair WikiLeaks has a twofold meaning.
On one side, it has turned out to be an obvious scandal, a scandal that is merely a scandal in the sense of hypocrisy that governs relations between states, citizens and the press.
On the other hand, it announces profound changes at international level, and gives a foretaste of the future dominated by regression.
But let's go ahead in turn.
The first aspect of WikiLeaks is the confirmation of the fact that every file created by an intelligence agency (an x-any nation) consists exclusively of newspaper clippings.
The "extraordinary" American revelations about Berlusconi's sexual habits do nothing more than what has been read for months anyway in every x-any journal (except for those who own Berlusconi), and Gaddafi's terrifyingly caricatured profile has long offered cabaret artists material for their sketches.
The rule that secret dossiers can only consist of news that is already known is essential for the dynamics of the intelligence services, and not only in this century.
If you go to a library dedicated to esoteric publications, you will realize that every work (about the Grail, the mystery of Rennes-le-Chateau, the Templars or the Rosicrucians) repeats exactly what has already been written in previous works.
This is not only because the author of occult texts does not want to publish research (still because he does not know where news about the non-existent could be found), but because those who devote themselves to occultism believe in nothing else but what they already know and confirm what they have already learned.
This is also Dan Brown's success mechanism.
The same is true of the secret files.
The informant is lazy, and lazy (or limited mind) is also the head of the secret service (otherwise, he could be whatever, for example, editor at Libération), who considers only true what he acknowledges.
The top secret information about Berlusconi, which the American Embassy in Rome had sent to the State Department, was the same as Newsweek had published the week before.
So why was such a fuss made about the revelations of these dossiers?
On one side, they say what every educated person already knows, namely that the embassies - at least since the end of the Second World War and since then also the heads of government can call each other or take a plane to meet for dinner - have lost their diplomatic function and, with the exception of some small representational tasks, have turned into spy centres.
Any viewer of investigative films knows this very well, and it does not happen out of hypocrisy that one does so to ignore this.
Nevertheless, the fact of publicly repeating it violates the task of hypocrisy and serves to put American diplomacy in a bad light.
Second, the idea that an x-any hacker can tap into the most secret secrets of the most powerful country in the world is a major blow to the prestige of the State Department.
In addition, the scandal brings less the victims than rather the "judges" in distress.
But let us devote ourselves to the profound nature of what has happened.
Formerly, at Orwell's time, all power could be bundled like a Big Brother, controlling every gesture of his subjects.
Orwell's prophecy could have turned out to be perfectly correct since then, where every movement can be controlled thanks to the phone, every transaction made, the hotel visited, the chosen highway and so on; the citizen would become the total victim of the eye of power.
But if one imagines what is going on today, that even the secret crypts of power can no longer escape the control of a hacker, the control course ceases to be directed unilaterally and becomes circular.
Power controls every citizen, but every citizen, or at least the hacker - chosen as the citizen's avenger - can learn the secrets of power.
But how can a power no longer be able to keep its own secrets?
It's true, Georg Simmel already said that a real secret is an empty secret (and an empty secret can never be revealed); it's also true that any knowledge of the character of Berlusconi or Merkel is basically a secret free of secret because it reveals the public sphere; but in the style of WikiLeaks, revealing that the secrets of Hillary Clinton were empty secrets means robbing them of any power.
