Climate: how France speaks out its financial promises
One year after the Copenhagen Treaty, it is time to examine the fast-resolved financing promises (also called "fast start" or premature financing) that have been implemented by developing countries.
And already the rough French fine speeches are revealed.
With the Copenhagen Treaty, developing countries committed to providing 30 billion dollars between 2010 and 2012.
The EU has promised EUR 7.2 billion over three years, France EUR 1.26 billion (i.e. EUR 420 million per year).
On the occasion of the opening of COP16, the EU has drawn up all the registers to convince its partners of its commitment to fast-start financing: detailed progress report by its Member States, press conference, large side events, distribution of brochures.
The transparency operation is remarkable and valued for its real value: developing countries and civil society would like all developed countries to do the same at the same level of precision.
The EU announces that it has released 2.2 billion euros in 2010, which will bring it on the right track to pay respect for its commitment of 7.2 billion in 2012.
But when you look into the detail, things are a little more complicated.
According to the Copenhagen Treaty, this money should be "new and additional" to ensure that an additional effort has been made without harming public development aid.
Unfortunately, there is no consensus on what "new and additional" means.
While the EU Commission had proposed harmonisation, certain member states, including France, have blocked the procedure.
Today, everyone chooses the benchmark he considers best.
For example, the EU Commission has chosen to be the benchmark for 2009: international financing will be maintained and will spend 150 million on funding "fast start" over three years.
Other countries have chosen similar benchmarks, either in terms of year or conditions at official development aid level.
In return, France felt that the financing of "all new projects" in 2010 was "new and additional".
In other words, there are no benchmarks for spending in the previous year or at the global level of official development assistance.
In concrete terms, the total amount of French support to developing countries can remain stable (or decrease) - France is pretending to comply with its commitment to "new and additional" financing.
Another crucial element is the breakdown into donations and loans.
There is no rule about this yet, and everyone chooses their computing mode.
Some, such as France, have 1 borrowed € as equivalent to 1 donated €.
Obviously, this is difficult to justify: the effort is not comparable.
If the use of loans for certain profitable investments (often projects linked to emission control based on the most effective technology) can be justified, it is deceptive to present the euro that is collected as an equivalent of a donated euro... Moreover, only the cost of the loan to the investor country should be counted as a commitment (i.e. the equivalent of an interest rate).
But France has nothing other than the following reasoning: it "respects" its commitment of 420 million euros by borrowing 91.5% (389.8 million euros) and donating 8.5%) 36.1 million euros - see also the EU document to convince itself.
France is the only country in the EU that uses loans to a large extent.
Germany demands 46%, while Denmark, the Netherlands or Slovakia (among other things) carry out 100% of their obligations with donations.
In other words, if the vast majority of the European Union spends €1 to fulfil its obligations, France gives just 10 cents and means a comparable commitment.
Nice hokuspokus!
All in all, France operates in its fast-start financing with a double dizzy: partly with a further development of the action over time and partly with the reality of the financial commitment.
France succeeds in making it believe that it has spent 420 million "new and additional" million in accordance with its promises, saving 36.1 million euros.
The manipulation of the Ministry of Finance (since it seems that it was Bercy who carried out the arbitrage) could have a double negative effect; one EU-internal (why do the other member states continue with the donation, if it is enough to lend?) and then in the negotiations, since the developing countries do not allow themselves to be completely deceived...
The chapter of premature financing is only a small question for a relatively short period of time compared to the overall debate on climate.
But it could be the drop too much in the immense machinery of the UNFCCC.
Let us hope that this will not be the case.
However, it is essential to learn his lesson from this first year of premature financing.
First and foremost, France could announce a change in its way of accounting for 2011 and 2012, in a spirit of respect for its commitments and balancing justice with the other countries of the European Union.
Above all, however, France could bring forward the discussions on the subject of long-term financing (another, crucial and currently discussed topic): one does not escape the question of "predictability" or the method of accounting for its loans.
France could change its position in order to be as progressive on the issues of dispute as it is on other matters.
So the hope is based on the new Environment Minister Kosciusko-Morizet, who will arrive in Cancun next week.
A surprising announcement about France's fast-start and its vision of "predictability" as well as the use of loans would naturally raise the international basis of trust necessary for further discussions.
